answers.body_markdown:
In JS, the [comma operator (`,`)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Comma_Operator) evaluates all operands, and returns the last. 

So, in your case, it is equivalent to:

    var val=15;

The `5` and `10` are evaluated and then silently dropped.

But consider the following:

    var i=0;
    var val=(i++,15);
    
    console.log(i) //1
    console.log(val) //15

The value of `i` is increased by `1`, and it returns `15`, combined to a single expression.

