As suggested by Kyle,

    /[a-z]+-\d{1,2}-[a-z][0-9]?/

does the job. Let&#39;s break it down:

    [] &lt;-- matches a group of characters
    [a-z] &lt;-- defines the matching range of characters (a-z), case-sensitive
    [a-z]+ &lt;-- says &quot;one or more occurances from the group a-z

    - &lt;-- matches the character &quot;-&quot;
    \d &lt;-- matches any digit (0-9). The \ makes sure you don&#39;t mean &quot;d&quot; here
    \d{1,2} &lt;-- means &quot;must occure between 1 and 2 times&quot;
    
    - &lt;-- matches the character &quot;-&quot;
    [a-z] &lt;-- defines the matching range of characters (a-z), case-sensitive
    [0-9] &lt;-- same as \d. matches any digit (0-9). expects exactly one of that group.
    ? &lt;-- marks the last group [0-9] optional, meaning it can occur zero to many times.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const pattern = /[a-z]+-\d{1,2}-[a-z][0-9]?/;

    const examples = [
      &quot;england-7-a&quot;,
      &quot;england-12-a1&quot;,
      &quot;-7-a&quot;,
      &quot;england&quot;,
      &quot;england-123-a&quot;,
      &quot;england-12-12&quot;,
      &quot;england-12-A123&quot;
    ]

    examples.forEach(str =&gt; console.log(`&quot;${str}&quot; does ${pattern.test(str) ? &#39;&#39; : &#39;not &#39;}match the pattern.`));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If you need case-insensive checking, replace `a-z` with `a-zA-Z`.
